</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/unyssarainwhisper.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nyssa Rainwhisper</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://arnemetia.homestead.com/files/MiscImages/bluepawbullet.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/28/01 4:51:50 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://arnemetia.homestead.com/files/DAoC/lynxhead.jpg WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=116></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What happened to fear spells?  Camping?</span><hr size=1> Well no matter how much Mythic or any other MMORPG company, for that matter would like to prevent camping, I honestly don't think it's 100% possible.  Mythic has done a decent job minimizing outdoor camping.  Dungeons for example, will always be camped.  What's wrong with named mobs dropping special items?  They're a special mob, why not drop a special item?  And why shouldn't dungeons have better loot? They're harder to fight in.  I've died many more times per night fighting in a dungeon than all my times added outdoors.<br>
<br>
People camp a specific spot in a dungeon for many reasons, one being that that spot is potentially safe for them.  Like you said, the ones moving around are the ones that gets wiped out.  Well, greater the risk, greater the gain.  Moving around increases your risks.  <br>
<br>
Of course you're not gonna be able to see further down a hall.  Your vision can only go so far.  We're playing a fantasy game, not a superheroes game.  Our characters don't have extended vision.  It also would make no sense to create a dungeon with mobs that are all the same lvl.  Dungeons are designed for you to group, strategize, and grow into.<br>
<br>
Quite frankly I've gotten more and better items outdoors than in a dungeon.  I've gotten a lot of magic items which I can wear for longer periods of time outdoors than in dungeons where I've only gotten armor that greens out after a few lvls.  I like fighting in dungeons because it's a LOT more challenging than fighting outdoors.  Outdoor fighting makes it too easy to run away when things go wrong, whereas in a dungeon, you're forced to strategize, and think.<br>
<br>
As for fear spells.  Sure most mythological and fantasy games have them.  But is Mythic obligated to put them in DAoC?  They're allowed to be different.  I think a lot of us are just too used to play EQ and expecting certain things.  We just need to unlearn what we've learned in EQ and start fresh.  While DAoC is similar in many ways, it is still a whole new game.  I'm sure EQ lacked somethings that was in D&amp;D, but people made do with what they were given.<br>
<br>
You don't need fear spells since you can easily out run a mob and have it forget you with sprint.  Other than fear kiting what else do you need it for?<br>
<br>
I honestly wouldn't wanna play DAoC if it was EXACTLY like EQ.  I mean, I worked hard to achieve what I got in EQ and lvl my chars, why leave if it wasn't for something different? <p><CENTER>
