Well sweetie, perhaps you should change your goal in DAoC. There are plenty of things for you to do other than lvling all the time. Try a trade skill...better yet, try 2 or 3 or 4.  That way you can make your own armor and don't have to wait for it to drop.  Not to mention you can make a lot of money doing consignment quests for various NPCs, as well as help out other realm-mates in making armor for them. You'll see that trade skills in DAoC are a HUGE improvement than the ones in EQ.  At least you don't have to spend months gathering supplies in attempts to get your skill up ONE measly point.  (Don't believe me? Go to eqtraders.com and read the rants there from frustrated tailors and other people in pursuit of trade skills.)  Trade skills are a great way to break the monotony of lvling.  If you're gonna do nothing but pursue exp day in and day out, well yeah you're gonna be bored no matter which game you play or how well the game is developed.<br>
<br>
And I really beg to differ that EQ quests are more detailed than DAoC ones. But then again, it's all a matter of opinion I guess.  But consider this: every quest given to my by my trainer in DAoC have been worthwhile and has an interesting story to it.  When was the last time someone around 15th lvl was able to do a quest that yielded a worthwhile item in EQ?  Epic quests in EQ are a joke no less.  It forces you to bicker with other people on your server over whose right it is to kill an insanely tough mob that requires you to recruit 40 people to defeat. Epic quests in DAoC?  It has a storyline, I can start it at 15th, yields some really nice sub items as I go along, and it continues for a good 15 lvls.  Most importantly, I don't need 40 people with uber equipment to help me.  I can accomplish what I need with a few skillful people.<br>
<br>
Sure most of us play to gain that new lvl or skill so our characters can be stronger and better.  But then again, most of us don't force ourselves to log on to a game to do that.  I personally enjoy the game, therefore, I log on and play it.  If I don't enjoy it anymore, or if it bores me, then I cancel the account and stop playing.  Hence why I no longer play EQ. ;)  Sure most of us don't enjoy looking forward to the same routine, (unless we get paid to do it, IE work) but if you're gonna enjoy a game, then you have to explore your options within the game to find ways to make it fun and exciting.  If you're forcing yourself to enjoy games, why do you even bother with buying them and playing them to begin with?  Do something else you know you will like.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think Mythic's done a good job so far with DAoC's concept. <p><CENTER>
