</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ujerit.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jerit</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/29/01 8:44:19 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What happened to fear spells?  Camping?</span><hr size=1> There are actually a number of spell types from EQ that aren't in DAoC. Spells like gate, self ports and group ports don't exist in DAoC. On the other hand DAoC has a damage enhancement for weapons spell line (for several classes) that EQ doesn't (and no these aren't the equivalent of EQ damage shields, DAoC has it's own line of damage shield spells). It's just a question of style.<br>
<br>
When you think about any computer role-playing (term is used loosely for computer games) game there are actually very few base spell effects. There is direct damage, damage over time, protection, enhancement, healing, neutralizing and movement. Pretty much any spell or game effect can be lumped into one of these categories. It comes down to how it is implemented (what you call it and what the graphic effect looks like).<br>
<br>
Direct Damage can be anything from a sword hit to a fire spell from a wizard. Damage over Time can be anything from an acid cloud spell with a set number of rounds of effect, to an elemental from a theurgist or a bleed component from an attack style.<br>
<br>
For ANY game it's just a question of what the effect is called, looks like and how it's implemented.<br>
<br>
Is there camping? Sure there is. Is it better? No, but some people prefer it because it gives them a set (though typically diminishing returns) amount of experience in a given time with minimal risk. Moving through a dungeon while riskier provides better rewards in terms of experience. How? By your own statement you walk down the hallway and get jumped by 3-4 mobs at once. This gives you a HUGE experience bonus for fighting multiple mobs at once. In EQ in most dungeons you had to fight multiple mobs to break a 'room'. While this was supposed to provide a greater 'challenge' you were not rewarded for this greatly increased risk in any form or fashion. At least DAoC gives you a VERY visible reward for the risk you take.<br>
<br>
Even though some people fight over spawns it really isn't that big a deal (at least IMO) for a couple of reasons. First is that even if someone else does over half the damage they won't get all the exp for killing a mob you engaged first (or thought you did). They will merely get a portion of experience relative to the damage they did. Second is that the mobs respawn VERY quickly, two or three minutes is typical. Not like having to wait 29 minutes for the mob to respawn in say LGUK after some high level KS'ed a named from your group or DAYS for some of the quest mobs.<br>
<br>
You really should explore some of the other options like the quests (while they aren't excellent full blown novels, they do hold up much better than EQ quests for consistency) and tradeskills. I could probably be at least 10 levels higher than I am on several characters, but I sit around messing with tradeskills and consignments for a good bit each level and make good cash doing it as well. For me this really breaks up the leveling treadmill.<br>
<br>
Anytime I find myself having to force myself to play a game, I take a couple of weeks off from the game. If after the break I still don't like the game I'll take a couple more weeks off. If I still am reluctant to play the game then it's time for me to move on to another game.<br>
<br>
I will agree with Broomhilda in that a lot of times the hype for a new game is blown out of proportion. The thing to remember is that little things that make one game different from another will have a large impact on how it makes different people feel about the game. Broomhilda misses the 'equipment cusomizing of EQ'. Personally I LOATHED having to go camp a specific named spawn for a specific piece of equipment. Different tastes in gameplay. ::shrug::<br>
<br>
Me? I have kept my EQ account because I wanted to see how I felt about EQ after a couple of months and how I felt about DAoC after a month or so. I'll be cancelling my EQ account in the near future.<br>
<br>
Why DAoC over EQ? I much prefer the downtime to gaming ratio in DAoC to EQ. I much prefer the quests in DAoC. I prefer the tradeskills. I like seeing how much experience I'm getting for killing a mob (and the different bonuses that encourage you to take on camps and then move on). I like the interface with the exception of F6 for entering basic melee combat. I like the tradeoff of using my endurance to up my damage (either through spellcasting or melee) at the expense of reducing my ability to sprint away from the mob if I get in trouble. I like that mobs give up after a short while and will quickly move back to their 'camp' area if the mob can't catch me and that they won't spread agro on me to every bloody mob in an entire zone that they happen to pass even remotely close to. I also love the fact that I don't have to look at a bloody spellbook for over half my gaming time if I'm playing a caster. There are numerous other areas where I prefer DAoC over other products currently available.<br>
<br>
Is DAoC perfect? Hardly. Do I think DAoC is for everyone? No. It has it's little flaws as well as some larger flaws, but overall I much prefer DAoC to any other product that is on the market now.<br>
<br>
Just my little 2 cp. <p>Jerit  Albion Mercenary<BR>
