</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubroomhilda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Broomhilda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/29/01 12:23:21 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ......</span><hr size=1> Just to give you example Tandaina, almost all the items i received from Mithra Tomb are now green.  This was about 2-3 lvls ago.  I'll have to upgrade them next lvl when i assume they'll turn gray.  So i basically was able to use them for i'd say about 3 lvls before i'm forced to upgrade.  I didnt mean customizing in terms of looking different but thats my fault since i should've clarified.  I dont really care about looks until i get higher lvl like in EQ and have most of the stuff i want.  Theres no way i'm spending my life savings of 10gold on a dye that only dyes one piece of clothing.  That 10gold is as valuable to me as anything i have, if not more.  I scrounged like a pauper for that much gold.  I meant customizing more along the lines of emphasis on equipment and being proud of what you've acquired so far.  I mean if i finally get a cool piece of armour or a cool staff i want to be able to use it for awhile.  Not have to throw it away after a few lvls.  Basically, i just dont think DAOC puts much of an emphasis on equipment, most of its emphasis is on spec points as you lvl.  I'm not a big fan of that i guess.<br>
<br>
My lvl 15 epic quest includes a decent necklace as well as a staff i believe.  I got a pretty nice staff (ebony) already as well as a decent alternate staff that improves my power in specializations(cant recall name rignt now).   My lvl 15 epic requires me to go all over Albion searching for certain npc's and killing some things.  To me its not worth it when its gonna go green after a few lvls.  However the lvl 30 epic staff looks like its worth doing from what i've read on that so i might end up doing that if i make it that high.  <br>
<br>
Actually, not all mmorpgs are lvling treadmills.  UO wasnt but UO uses a skills system. kinda like specializing, but think more along the lines of specializing in skills where you can take points back by allowing those skills to detiorate.  Which is why i have so much praise for UO even though i hate OSI, because its different than the rest(EQ, AC, DAOC, AO).  In fact, I still dont understand why a 1st person mmorpg hasnt gone the UO-skills system route.  It would work great in a game that involves high lvl PvP, and it would dare to be different as well as set a new standard. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukiatek2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kiatek2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/29/01 2:57:15 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> well</span><hr size=1> if you soloed to get those items you might have received them later than if you grouped to get them.  i was a in group and (at level 19) got a level 25 necklace.  I gave it a friend that could use it more (he was 22 or 23) but he can use that necklace probably til at least level 30.  so that is 7 or 8 levels.  then he can pass it down to someone else below him that its useful to.  now you may have been able to solo a purple (by several levels) but no way i can lol to get that necklace.   <br>
<br>
that isnt the only incident i have seen, so this a trend i have noticed in the game.  since you can tackle harder stuff with a group of ppl (typically), you have the potential to get higher level items that you can use longer.<br>
<br>
btw not saying this is true in every instance, just from the majority of my experiences. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ugoldmundtargari.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goldmund TargaRi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/29/01 3:17:08 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ......</span><hr size=1> Hey Broom, I'm not gonna knock your opinions.  In fact I agree with a lot of what you have to say.  However, I think a lot of your frustration is a result of this being such a new game.  This can be frustrating for two reasons: one, there isn't an overwhelming amount of content available (EQ was exactly the same way at the beginning, possibly worse even); and two, you may not be aware of much of the content that IS available.<br>
<br>
Now stop me if I'm wrong, but it sounds from your posts that you play a friar in Albion.  If so, there are several quests that you should work on that result in very nice gear.  And despite how it may seem, equipment plays a VERY big role in the effectiveness of your character.  If you are using store bought weapons and armor, you are really shortchanging yourself.  A big oversight that people tend to make is neglecting the Quality stat on a piece of gear.  Quality directly impacts the AF on armor, and damage on weapons.  Store bought stuff maxes out at 85% qua, mob drops are 89%, player crafted is 90-99%, and quested pieces are usually 100%  So your lvl 15 quest leggings (assuming friar) are going to be better than anything else you could put in that slot for a good 5 levels (not to mention that I got nearly 6 bubs of exp from completing the quest).<br>
<br>
Other quests that yield great rewards:<br>
<br>
<a href=http://www.themonastery.net/quests3.html>Staff of Life</a><br>
<a href=http://www.themonastery.net/quests11.html>Siom's Staff</a><br>
<a href=http://www.themonastery.net/quests8.html>Frip's Dad</a><br>
<a href=http://daoc.warcry.com/quests/detail_quest.php?quest=14>Search for Sil</a><br>
<a href=http://daoc.warcry.com/quests/detail_quest.php?quest=39>Hunt for Arachneida</a><br>
<br>
I'm hard pressed to think of even one quest in EQ that yields a decent piece of gear for someone 15 and under.<br>
<br>
In an earlier post you mentioned Mithra being good exp at 12-13.  I'd actually argue that you should head to Mithra at 6-7 and leave at 11-12.  If you'd gotten your armor at a lower level (when it was still orange-yellow) you would get MUCH more use out of it.  At level 15 you should start hunting for Bloodied Leather armor (drops from welsh hobgoblins in Llyn Barfog and undead romans in Cornwall) which will last you until level 25 or so.<br>
<br>
Also, I wouldn't sweat only having 10gp at level 15.  I can make 10gp hunting in an evening now at 23 (in a good group, not a chance solo).  However if you want to accumulate some wealth, you simply must pick up a tradeskill.  I had well over 100gp at level 15 from my work in tailoring.  <br>
<br>
Well I've rambled enough here, but hopefully I've given you a few alternatives to the kill loot kill loot monotony. <p><img src=http://www.alltel.net/~mr81645/godzillasigDAoC.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/unyssarainwhisper.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nyssa Rainwhisper</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://arnemetia.homestead.com/files/MiscImages/bluepawbullet.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/30/01 3:21:06 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://arnemetia.homestead.com/files/DAoC/lynxhead.jpg WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=116></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What happened to fear spells?  Camping?</span><hr size=1> Well first off, Broomhilda.  Games should never be something you need to motivate yourself to get into.  Why are you doing that to yourself?  I mean, motivate yourself to get up in the morning to go to work, motivate yourself to go exercise instead of vegging out on the couch, but motivating yourself to play a game?  Something doesn't sound right here.  You shouldn't have to force yourself to do something that should be naturally enjoyable and pleasurable.<br>
<br>
Fine, you don't like tradeskills, fine, you don't like lvling, fine, you don't like camping, but have you ever sat down and thought, &quot;hmm that's what ALL MMORPGs are about.  If I don't like those things, maybe MMORPGs aren't right for me?&quot;  I mean, is someone making you play these games that you so blatantly don't like?  <br>
<br>
I don't really know a MMORPG that doesn't require you to gain experience and lvl before you can advance to the greater features in the game.  If you think about it, games kinda reflect real life.  At low lvls you must kill mobs and gain experience, much like going to school.  Then when you're experienced and wise enough you can engage in tougher mobs, and fight against other people.  IE: the real world and work.  You can't be successful in the working world without an education ya know.  And think of tradeskills as if they were like sports back in school.  They're a form of distraction away from the every day grind.<br>
<br>
If you really want to play a game, then why don't you look into games that has what you like.  Play a Playstation or a Nintendo game.  Last I recall, games from the Legend of Zelda series don't require lvling, and don't have tradeskills, yet they allow you to adventure and explore the land.<br>
<br>
By the way you're sounding, I honestly think you're wasting your time investing in MMORPGs. <p><CENTER>
